@page "/cultures/translation"
@rendermode InteractiveServer
@inherits PageBase

<h1>Translations</h1>

<p>
    Three idiomatic ways to translate a phrase. All return <code>Translated</code> — a
    value object with implicit conversion to <code>string</code>, so it composes naturally
    with HTML output.
</p>

<section class="card">
    <h2>1. Inline</h2>
    <pre>Culture.Translate("Welcome").Value
Culture.Translate("Welcome to {0}", Tenant.Settings.Site.Title)</pre>
    <p>→ @Culture.Translate("Welcome").Value</p>
    <p>→ @Culture.Translate("Welcome to {0}", "Zonit").Value</p>
</section>

<section class="card">
    <h2>2. Try your own phrase</h2>
    <input class="input" @bind="_input" @bind:event="oninput" />
    <p>Translated: <strong>@Culture.Translate(_input).Value</strong></p>
    <p class="muted">Each unmatched key is recorded by the missing-translation tracker.</p>
</section>

<section class="card">
    <h2>3. DataAnnotations integration</h2>
    <p>
        <code>PageEditBase&lt;T&gt;</code> calls <code>Culture.Translate(error)</code> on every
        validation message. Localising a form is therefore <em>just</em> a matter of providing
        translations for the static error strings — see <code>/components/page-edit</code>.
    </p>
</section>

@code {
    string _input = "Hello there";
}
